===Verb===
{{en-verb|hears|hearing|heard}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[perceive]] sounds through the [[ear]]. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}
#: {{ux|en|I was deaf, and now I can '''hear'''.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[perceive]] (a sound, or something producing a sound) with the [[ear]], to [[recognize]] (something) in an auditory way. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}
#: {{ux|en|I '''heard''' a sound from outside the window.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1898|author={{w|Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill}}
|title={{w|The Celebrity}}|chapter=4
|passage=Mr. Cooke at once began a tirade against the residents of Asquith for permitting a sandy and generally disgraceful condition of the roads. So roundly did he vituperate the inn management in particular, and with such a loud flow of words, that I trembled lest he should be '''heard''' on the veranda.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To exercise this faculty [[intentionally]]; to [[listen]] to. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}
#* '''1526''', {{w|William Tyndale}}, trans. ''Bible'', {{w|Gospel of John|John}} X:
#*: Agayne there was dissencion amonge the iewes for these sayinges, and many of them sayd: He hath the devyll, and is madde: why '''heare''' ye hym?
#* {{quote-book|year=1935|author=[https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/288354.George_Goodchild George Goodchild]
|title=Death on the Centre Court|chapter=3
|passage=It had been his intention to go to Wimbledon, but as he himself said: “Why be blooming well frizzled when you can '''hear''' all the results over the wireless. And results are all that concern me.&nbsp;[&hellip;]”}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To listen favourably to; to [[grant]] (a request etc.). {{defdate|from 10th c.}}
#: {{ux|en|Eventually the king chose to '''hear''' her entreaties.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To receive information about; to come to [[learn]] of. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}
#* '''1667''', {{w|John Milton}}, ''{{w|Paradise Lost}}'':
#*: Adam, soon as he '''heard''' / The fatal Trespass don by Eve, amaz'd, / Astonied stood and Blank [...].
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[listen]] to (a person, case) in a court of law; to [[try]]. {{defdate|from 12th c.}}
#: {{ux|en|Your case will be '''heard''' at the end of the month.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|informal}} To [[sympathize]] with; to share the feeling or opinion of.
#: {{ux|en|You're tired of all the ads on TV? I '''hear''' ya.}}

